 vision, highlighting its real-world successes in fostering grassroots budgeting campaigns in such cities as New York, Boston, and Chicago. As more and more communities turn to participatory budgeting as a means of engaging citizens, prioritizing civic projects, and allocating local, state, and federal funding, this cogent volume will offer guidance and inspiration to others who want to transform democracy in the United States and elsewhere."The Participatory Budgeting Project exemplifies the essential features the award committee was looking for in its inaugural recipient. Political and economic inequality is part of the American national discussion, and participatory budgeting helps empower marginalized groups that do not normally take part in a process that is so critical for democratic life."— John Gastil, Director of the McCourtney Institute for Democracy  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aBudget processxCitizen participationxUnited States. 0aBudget processzUnited StatesxCitizen participation. 0aLocal budgetsxCitizen participationxUnited States. 0aLocal budgetszUnited StatesxCitizen participation. 0aPolitical participationxUnited States. 0aPolitical participationzUnited States. 0aPolitical planningxCitizen participationxUnited States. 0aPolitical planningzUnited StatesxCitizen participation. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aU.S. History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh  alaurence and lynne brown democracy medal, participatory budgeting project, public spending, budgeting campaigns, civic projects, transforming democracy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145606040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801456060423Cover